\chapter{The \texttt{cli.track} module and
         the \texttt{track} subcommands}%
\chapterprecis{Written by Copilot and Dan-Claude.
               Reviewed by Daniel Bosk.}
\label{cli.track}

In this chapter we introduce the subcommands found under [[nytid track]],
it's the [[cli.track]] module for time tracking functionality.

\section{Design Overview and Rationale}

The track command allows teachers to track time spent on various course-related activities
such as meetings, grading, preparation time, lectures, etc. The system is designed around
several key principles:

\subsection{Flat Label System}
The core design uses independent labels (tags) to categorize work. Labels are flat, not 
hierarchical, allowing maximum flexibility in organizing and filtering tracked time.
For example, tracking with labels [[DD1310]], [[lecture]], [[preparation]] creates three
independent tags that can be started and stopped individually:
\begin{itemize}
\item Each label tracks independently.
\item Labels can be stopped in any order.
\item A label already being tracked is silently continued rather than
  duplicated when started again.
\item Labels can be combined for multi-dimensional categorization.
\item Labels started together in one command form a \enquote{batch}
  that can be stopped as a unit.
\end{itemize}

This allows for flexible reporting and analysis, such as:
\begin{itemize}
\item All time spent on [[DD1310]] (regardless of activity).
\item All [[lecture]] time (regardless of course).
\item Time spent on [[DD1310]] and [[lecture]] (intersection).
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Batch Stopping Behavior}
When multiple labels are started together in a single command, they form a "batch" that
can be stopped together. This is useful for tracking related activities:
\begin{itemize}
\item [[nytid track start DD1310]] starts [[DD1310]] alone (batch 1).
\item [[nytid track start lecture prep]] starts [[lecture]] and [[prep]]
  together (batch 2).
\item [[nytid track stop]] stops the most recent batch
  ([[lecture]] and [[prep]]).
\item [[nytid track stop]] again stops the next batch ([[DD1310]]).
\end{itemize}

You can still stop individual labels by specifying them:
[[nytid track stop lecture]],
or stop all labels at once with [[nytid track stop --all]].

\subsection{Resume Functionality}
The system remembers the most recently stopped labels, allowing you to resume tracking
without retyping label names:
\begin{itemize}
\item After stopping labels, [[nytid track start]] (without arguments)
  resumes them.
\item Useful when interrupted and wanting to continue the same activity.
\item Example: [[nytid track start mail]] is interrupted,
  [[nytid track stop]] stops mail tracking; later
  [[nytid track start]] resumes mail tracking.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Switch Functionality}
\label{sec:design-switch-functionality}

The [[switch]] command provides a context-switch mechanism: interrupt
the current work, do something else, then pick up where you left off.
Calling [[nytid track switch email]] stops the current labels, saves
them as the one alternate context, and starts [[email]].  Calling
[[nytid track switch]] with no arguments swaps back to that saved
context.

The design keeps one saved alternate context.  A forward [[switch]]
saves the labels it interrupts, and a bare [[switch]] swaps back to
that saved set.  A second forward switch replaces the previously saved
set rather than pushing a deeper stack.

\subsection{Independent Label Tracking}
Each label in an active session tracks time independently with its own start time.
Labels can be:
\begin{itemize}
\item Started individually or in groups.
\item Stopped individually or in groups.
\item Annotated with notes at any time.
\item Queried to see current status.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Persistent Data Storage}
All tracking data is persisted in JSON format using nytid's StorageRoot system for
consistency with other nytid components. The system maintains two separate data files:
\begin{description}
\item[Completed entries] Historical tracking data for analysis and export.
\item[Active session] Current tracking state that survives application restarts.
\end{description}

\subsection{Multi-Worker Support}

The tracking system supports parallel tracking by different workers.
Each worker is identified by a name string (defaulting to
[[\$USER]]) and maintains an independent active session file.
This enables scenarios like a teacher and an AI assistant tracking
time simultaneously on the same project without interference.

The design separates \emph{active state} from \emph{historical data}:
\begin{description}
\item[Per-worker session files] Each worker gets its own active
  session file ([[current_session_me.json]],
  [[current_session_dan-claude.json]], etc.), preventing
  concurrent trackers from overwriting each other's state.
\item[Shared history] Completed entries from all workers are
  stored in a single [[tracking_data.json]] file, with a [[who]]
  field identifying the worker. This simplifies analysis and
  export across workers.
\end{description}

All commands accept a [[--who]]/[[-w]] option (defaulting to
[[\$USER]]). The [[status]] command without [[--who]] shows all
active workers, while [[stats]] and [[export]] can optionally
filter by worker.

Backward compatibility is maintained: old session files without a
worker suffix are treated as belonging to the default worker, and
historical entries without a [[who]] field default to \enquote{me}
when loaded (preserving the identity recorded at the time).

\subsection{Multi-format Export Capability}
The system supports multiple export formats (ICS, JSON, CSV) to integrate with different
tools and workflows that teachers use for time management and reporting.

