@

After resolving labels, we start tracking and report what happened.
Any [[--replace]] handling is delegated to [[start_tracking_labels()]] so
the discard and restart happen against fresh on-disk state rather than
against this earlier snapshot.

When [[start]] launches a command or tmux shell, it may need to derive one
extra label from the command name, validate tmux usage, and choose between
the plain tmux shell path and the prompted direct-shell path.

Launch mode also needs a clear ownership rule for labels.  If a label is
already active and we launch a child process without saying what should
happen to the existing session, the command would appear to belong to that
label but the automatic shutdown path could leave the old session running.
We therefore require launch-bound labels to be inactive unless the user
explicitly picks one of two escape hatches: [[--replace]] (discard the old
session and restart) or [[--continue]] (keep the old session and bind the
child to it).  The shutdown path treats both cases identically---one
[[TrackingEntry]] per label at child exit---so the only difference is
whether the original start time survives.

The same rule must also cover the implicit label contributed by
[[--command]].  Otherwise a launch could smuggle in an already-active
command label after the preflight check and silently downgrade a conflict
to [[Already tracking]].

The effective launch label set should also be the one we report back to the
user.  If an explicit label matches the implicit command basename, keeping
the raw pre-deduplicated list would produce noisy output such as
[[Already tracking: echo, echo]] even though the session state correctly
tracks only one [[echo]] label.

Track and todo should also present launch context the same way.  We therefore
compute one context string up front and reuse it for tmux window names and
as a best-effort [[PS1]] seed.  In tmux the user's [[~/.bashrc]] will
likely overwrite [[PS1]] during normal startup, so the tmux window name is
the primary context indicator for pane and window launches.

