\subsubsection{Time Offset Support}

Teachers often forget to start tracking immediately when they begin an activity.
The [[--offset]] option allows backdating the start time by a relative amount,
such as \enquote{I started 30 minutes ago.}
The [[offset_opt]] and [[at_opt]] definitions use generic wording because they
are reused by [[stop]], [[switch]], and [[add]]---each command interprets the
offset or time relative to its own action.

<<argument and option definitions>>=
offset_opt = typer.Option(
    "--offset", "-o",
    help="Offset current time "
         "(e.g., '-30m', '-1.5h', '30' for minutes)")
@

<<start command options>>=
offset: Annotated[Optional[str], offset_opt] = None,
@

<<start command docstring examples>>=
nytid track start DD1310 --offset -30m        # Forgot to start on time
@

\subsubsection{Absolute Time Support}

While offsets work well for recent activities, they become awkward for absolute 
times (\enquote{What's the offset from now to 2pm?}). The [[--at]] option 
specifies an exact time.

<<argument and option definitions>>=
at_opt = typer.Option(
    "--at",
    help="Override current time "
         "(e.g., '14:30' or '2024-12-13 14:30')")
@

<<start command options>>=
at: Annotated[Optional[str], at_opt] = None,
@

<<start command docstring examples>>=
nytid track start meeting --at 14:30          # Meeting began at 2:30 PM
nytid track start                             # Resume last stopped labels
nytid track start DD1310 --who Dan-Claude     # Track work for another worker
@

\subsubsection{Replacing an Already-Active Label}

Without [[--replace]], re-issuing [[track start labelA]] when [[labelA]]
is already active has no effect: the label is silently continued and
reported as \enquote{Already tracking}.  This is the safe default---a
typo does not corrupt history.

With [[--replace]], the active session for the named labels is discarded
first via [[discard_labels]], and those labels are then re-started at the
offset or absolute time.  The typical use case is time-correction: the
user forgot to start tracking and now wants to backdate the session.  The
abandoned entry never reaches the history file, so no cleanup is needed
afterwards.

The flag is only meaningful for labels that are already active; for labels
that are not yet tracked, [[--replace]] has no observable effect---it just
starts them normally.

<<argument and option definitions>>=
replace_opt = typer.Option(
    "--replace", "-r",
    help="If a label is already active, discard its "
         "current session and restart it from the "
         "given offset/time.")
@

<<start command options>>=
replace: Annotated[bool, replace_opt] = False,
@

<<start command docstring examples>>=
nytid track start labelA --offset -60m --replace  # Restart active label earlier
@

\subsubsection{Continuing an Already-Active Label in a New Launch}

The [[--replace]] flag is the right answer when the user wants to
\emph{correct} the start time of an active label.  It is the
\emph{wrong} answer when the user just wants to keep working on the
same thing in a fresh tmux window or pane: the in-progress session
would be discarded, and the minutes already accumulated would
disappear.

The [[--continue]] flag covers that second case.  With [[--continue]],
launch mode (i.e.\ [[--window]], [[--pane]], or [[--command]]) accepts
labels that are already active: the existing session is preserved
untouched (no [[discard_labels]], no new history entry, original start
time unchanged), and the launched child process is bound to the same
labels via the normal window/pane-labels path.  When the window or
pane exits, the ordinary shutdown path stops the labels and records a
single [[TrackingEntry]] covering the original start time through the
child's exit.

That shutdown obligation belongs to the full effective launch label set,
not just the subset that happened to be newly started for this launch.
We therefore freeze the deduplicated ownership set in
[[launch_owned_labels]] during launch setup and reuse it for both direct
subprocess cleanup and the detached tmux finalizer.

The two flags express different intents and are mutually exclusive in
spirit (though the code tolerates either one being set): pick
[[--replace]] to rewrite the start time, pick [[--continue]] to
preserve it.

Outside launch mode [[--continue]] is a no-op: the default behaviour
of [[track start]] on already-active labels is to silently continue
them and report \enquote{Already tracking}, so the flag has nothing
extra to do there.

<<argument and option definitions>>=
continue_opt = typer.Option(
    "--continue", "-C",
    help="If a label is already active, keep its "
         "current session and bind it to the new "
         "window/pane/command instead of failing.")
@

<<start command options>>=
continue_labels: Annotated[bool, continue_opt] = False,
@

<<start command docstring examples>>=
nytid track start devel nytid -W --continue  # Bind active labels to new window
@

\subsubsection{Worker Identity}

The [[--who]] option identifies which worker is tracking. This enables
parallel tracking by different people (or agents) without interference,
since each worker maintains an independent active session file.

<<argument and option definitions>>=
who_opt = typer.Option(
    "--who", "-w",
    help="Worker identity (default: $USER)",
    autocompletion=complete_workers)
@

<<start command options>>=
who: Annotated[str, who_opt] = default_username,
@

\subsubsection{Launching a Command or a Tmux Shell}

Sometimes starting a label should immediately hand control to another tool:
mail in [[mutt]], a build in [[make]], or a shell in a dedicated tmux pane.
Rather than keeping a separate subcommand for that workflow, we let
[[start]] grow into it.

With [[--command]], the command's basename becomes an additional implicit
label.  For example, [[nytid track start work --command
/usr/local/bin/neomutt]] tracks both [[work]] and [[neomutt]], while the
full command string remains in the description so the history still records
what was launched.  With [[--pane]] or [[--window]] but no command,
[[start]] opens the user's default shell inside tmux through the same
plain-shell path as [[todo start]], so normal shell startup still runs.

<<argument and option definitions>>=
command_opt = typer.Option(
    "--command", "-c",
    help="Program and arguments to run while tracking "
         "(parsed with shlex; no shell syntax)")
@

<<start command options>>=
command: Annotated[Optional[str], command_opt] = None,
pane: Annotated[bool, pane_opt] = False,
window: Annotated[bool, window_opt] = False,
@

<<start command docstring examples>>=
nytid track start email -c "mutt"            # Track email while launching mutt
nytid track start grading -P                  # Open a tracked shell in tmux pane
nytid track start admin -W                    # Open a tracked shell in tmux window
@

\subsubsection{Non-Blocking Tmux Launch}

By default, tmux launches return immediately and keep their labels tied
to the pane or window.  When the pane exits, a tmux hook stops those
same labels if they are still active.  [[--block]] instead waits for the
tmux session to finish and then performs the same label-based stop in the
foreground process.

<<start command options>>=
    block: Annotated[Optional[bool], block_opt] = None,
@

<<start command docstring examples>>=
nytid track start grading -P                 # Tracked pane, return immediately
nytid track start grading -P --block         # Wait for the pane to finish
@

\subsubsection{Auto-Suspend on Focus Change}

When a tmux pane loses focus (the user switches to another pane or
window), tracking continues even though the user is no longer working
in that context.  [[--auto-suspend]] installs [[pane-focus-out]] and
[[pane-focus-in]] hooks so that tracking pauses and resumes with the
pane's focus.  This produces many small completed entries rather than
one long one, but each entry accurately reflects \emph{attended} time.

The two launch modes differ in what counts as \enquote{leaving} the
tracked context.  With [[--pane]], tmux's [[pane-focus-out]] fires on
\emph{any} focus loss---including Alt-Tabbing to a browser---so pane
auto-suspend is aggressive.  With [[--window]], tracking follows the
tmux window's selection state rather than terminal focus: switching to a
browser does not suspend the session, only switching to another tmux
window does.  Use [[--window]] when looking things up in a browser is
part of the normal workflow.

The default is resolved through the config hierarchy documented in
\cref{track:configuration}: CLI flag overrides per-worker config,
which overrides global config, which defaults to true.

<<start command options>>=
    auto_suspend: Annotated[
        Optional[bool], auto_suspend_opt
    ] = None,
@

<<start command docstring examples>>=
nytid track start grading -P --no-auto-suspend  # No focus tracking
@

\subsubsection{Time-Boxed Tracking}

The [[--timeout]] option kills the subprocess after a specified duration,
preventing a forgotten session from accumulating hours.  It applies only
to direct subprocesses launched with [[--command]]---tmux panes are
interactive and the user can close them at will.

<<start command options>>=
timeout: Annotated[Optional[str], timeout_opt] = None,
@

<<start command docstring examples>>=
nytid track start grading -c "vim" --timeout 2h  # Stop after 2 hours
@

\subsubsection{Working Directory}

By default, a launched command runs in the caller's current directory
and inherits its environment.  The [[--wd]] option overrides the
working directory---useful when the tracking command is issued from a
different location than where the work should happen, for example
launching an editor inside a specific git repository:

<<start command options>>=
wd_path: Annotated[Optional[str],
                   wd_opt] = None,
@

<<start command docstring examples>>=
nytid track start grading -c "vim" --wd ~/courses/DD1310
@

The environment is always forwarded unconditionally to subprocesses,
so there is no [[--env]] flag here.  (The companion [[todo add]]
command \emph{does} offer [[--env]] and [[--here]] because it
persists the captured environment for later replay.)

We validate the path early so the user gets a clear error before
tracking starts rather than a confusing subprocess failure later:

<<resolve working directory>>=
if wd_path and not os.path.isdir(wd_path):
    typer.echo(
        f"Error: --wd directory does not "
        f"exist: {wd_path}",
        err=True,
    )
    raise typer.Exit(1)
@

\subsubsection{Calculating Start Time}

[[--offset]] and [[--at]] are mutually exclusive: both address the same
question (when did this session start?) from different angles, and
combining them would be ambiguous.  We treat this as a user error rather
than picking one silently, so the mistake is surfaced immediately instead
of producing a confusing entry with an unexpected timestamp.

<<calculate start time>>=
if offset is not None and at is not None:
    typer.echo("Error: Cannot use both --offset and --at options", err=True)
    raise typer.Exit(1)

start_time = datetime.datetime.now()

if at is not None:
    try:
        start_time = parse_at_time(at)
    except ValueError as e:
        typer.echo(f"Error: {e}", err=True)
        raise typer.Exit(1)
elif offset is not None:
    try:
        offset_delta = parse_offset(offset)
        start_time += offset_delta
    except ValueError as e:
        typer.echo(f"Error parsing offset '{offset}': {e}", err=True)
        raise typer.Exit(1)
@

When the user specifies a custom start time, we report it for confirmation:

<<report custom start time if used>>=
if at is not None or offset is not None:
    typer.echo(f"Start time: {start_time.strftime('%Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S')}")
@

