\subsubsection{Deferred Window Event Buffer}
\label{track:event-buffer}

The event buffer file lives in the tracking directory and is shared
across all tracked windows for one worker \emph{within one tmux
session}.  The filename therefore includes the tmux server key and the
tmux session ID.  Windows inside the same session must share one event
stream so that switching among them works, while different sessions or
different tmux servers must remain isolated.

When debugging unexpected history splits, we need to see both sides of
the deferred \emph{window-event} buffer: what each hook appended and
what transition that buffer eventually executed.  We therefore add an
environment-gated trace for this buffer only.  When
[[track.debug]] is truthy, nytid appends one line per buffer
append or buffer-triggered execution to a debug log in the tracking
directory and also emits best-effort desktop notifications via
[[notify-send]].  Append events notify individually, but one executed
transition produces only one notification summarizing the switch target
and the stop/start labels chosen from the buffer.  The notification path
must not affect tracking behaviour, so missing [[notify-send]] is
silently ignored.

Desktop notifications are inherently less reliable than the file log,
because tmux hook subprocesses only inherit whatever graphical session
environment the server can see.  The file log is therefore the primary
record, while notifications are a convenience for live observation.

Because the setting lives in nytid's configuration store rather than one
shell environment, tmux hooks see the same debug flag as interactive
commands.  That makes the instrumentation reliable across both the live
CLI and detached hook processes.

Tmux hook subprocesses also read pane/window context files without going
through the main tracking-state mutation helper.  We therefore guard
those files with their own lock so hook readers and command-side writers
see one coherent view.

<<helper functions>>=
def with_tmux_context_lock(callback):
    """Run ``callback`` while holding the tmux context lock."""
    ensure_tracking_dir()
    lock_file = get_tmux_context_lock_file()
    with open(lock_file, "w") as lock_handle:
        fcntl.flock(lock_handle, fcntl.LOCK_EX)
        try:
            return callback()
        finally:
            fcntl.flock(lock_handle, fcntl.LOCK_UN)
@

The debug flag is only used by the deferred-buffer diagnostics, so we
introduce [[TRACK_DEBUG_CONFIG]] immediately before that helper.

