After appending, we re-read the entire file and ask the matcher whether
one coherent deferred switch is now complete:

<<check trigger condition>>=
os.lseek(fd, 0, os.SEEK_SET)
content = os.read(fd, 1_000_000).decode()
lines = content.splitlines()
emit_window_event_debug(
    who,
    tmux_server_key,
    session_id,
    "append",
    event_line,
    content,
)

transition = find_window_event_transition(lines)
if transition is None:
    return

switch_target_tracked = transition["switch"]["target_tracked"]
switch_source_tracked = transition["switch"]["source_tracked"]
suppress_execution_notifications = False
last_stop_labels = []
last_stop_time = None
last_start_labels = []
last_start_time = None

if transition["stop_event"] is not None:
    last_stop_labels = transition["stop_event"]["labels"]
    last_stop_time = transition["stop_event"]["when"]
if transition["start_event"] is not None:
    last_start_labels = transition["start_event"]["labels"]
    last_start_time = transition["start_event"]["when"]

if transition["execution"] == "switch":
    <<execute deferred window switch>>
    os.ftruncate(fd, 0)
elif transition["execution"] == "stop":
    <<execute deferred window stop>>
    os.ftruncate(fd, 0)
elif transition["execution"] == "start":
    <<execute deferred window start>>
    os.ftruncate(fd, 0)
@

The execution step stops the old window's labels, then starts the new
window's labels.  Both operations pass [[update_tmux_context=False]]
because the tmux context files (window labels) are already correct---we
are just updating the tracking session state to match.

For debugging, the execution notifications also report whether the source
window was known to be tracked.  That makes the previously ambiguous
start-only case visible in the log: a [[from-tracked]] marker means the
buffer must wait for the pending [[stop]] line, while [[from-untracked]]
or an older marker without source information may execute immediately.

