\subsubsection{Suspend and Resume Helpers}

The suspend helper stops only the labels that are currently active
in the worker's session---any label already stopped (by the user
or another process) is silently skipped.  The subtle part is that
this filtering must happen inside the same locked mutation that
performs the stop.  A pre-lock snapshot can go stale between the
read and the write, leaving the suspend state file claiming that a
label was paused even though another command had already stopped it.

We therefore delegate to [[stop_tracking_labels_if_active()]] and
persist only the subset that helper actually stopped.  The state file
then records the truth rather than the caller's optimistic assumption.

<<helper functions>>=
def suspend_tracking_labels(
    who: str,
    labels: List[str],
    pane_id: str,
    tmux_server_key: str,
) -> None:
    """Suspend tracking for a pane that lost focus.

    Stops whichever of ``labels`` are still active and
    writes them to the pane's suspend state file.
    """
    _, _, stopped_labels = stop_tracking_labels_if_active(
        who=who,
        labels=labels,
        update_tmux_context=False,
    )
    if not stopped_labels:
        return
    state_path = suspend_state_path(
        pane_id, who, tmux_server_key,
    )
    write_suspend_state(state_path, stopped_labels)
@

We delete the state file \emph{before} restarting labels so that a
crash between the two steps never causes a double-resume---losing
an unfocused session is preferable to silently double-booking time.
If the file is absent (pane exited while unfocused, or user manually
stopped everything), the resume is a no-op.

<<helper functions>>=
def resume_tracking_labels(
    who: str,
    pane_id: str,
    tmux_server_key: str,
) -> None:
    """Resume tracking for a pane that regained focus.

    Reads the suspend state file and restarts the
    labels recorded there.  Deletes the file afterwards.
    """
    state_path = suspend_state_path(
        pane_id, who, tmux_server_key,
    )
    labels = read_suspend_state(state_path)
    if not labels:
        return

    delete_suspend_state(state_path)
    start_tracking_labels(
        who=who,
        labels=labels,
        start_time=datetime.datetime.now(),
        update_tmux_context=False,
    )
@

For nested [[track]] commands inside a tracked tmux window, we must not
trust inherited environment variables such as [[TMUX_WINDOW_ID]].  A new
tmux window created with [[^b c]] would inherit the shell environment
from the old one, falsely claiming to belong to the tracked window.
Instead we derive the current [[window_id]] from the live [[TMUX_PANE]]
every time, then constrain any state lookup to the current tmux server
namespace.

<<helper functions>>=
def get_tmux_window_id_for_pane(
    pane_id: str,
) -> Optional[str]:
    """Return the tmux window id containing ``pane_id``."""
    try:
        result = subprocess.run(
            [
                "tmux",
                "display-message",
                "-p",
                "-t",
                pane_id,
                "#{window_id}",
            ],
            capture_output=True,
            text=True,
            check=True,
        )
    except (subprocess.CalledProcessError, OSError):
        return None
    window_id = result.stdout.strip()
    if not window_id:
        return None
    return window_id
@

Before querying tmux for the current window, we check whether any
tracked-window state files exist in the current tmux server namespace at
all.  This avoids a subprocess call to tmux in the common case where
window tracking is not in use.

<<helper functions>>=
def has_tracked_window_state(
    who: str,
    tmux_server_key: str,
) -> bool:
    """Return whether this worker currently has tracked windows."""
    pattern = (
        f"window_labels_{sanitize_tmux_id(tmux_server_key)}_*"
        f"_{sanitize_who(who)}.json"
    )
    return any(get_tracking_dir().glob(pattern))
@

The main entry point for nested commands combines the guards above: it
resolves the live window from [[TMUX_PANE]], checks for existing
tracked-window state in the current tmux server, and only returns a
[[window_id]] when the window is already tracked by nytid.

<<helper functions>>=
def get_current_tracked_window_id(
    who: str,
    tmux_server_key: str,
) -> Optional[str]:
    """Return the live tmux window id if it is already tracked."""
    pane_id = os.environ.get("TMUX_PANE")
    if not pane_id:
        return None
    if not has_tracked_window_state(
        who, tmux_server_key,
    ):
        return None
    window_id = get_tmux_window_id_for_pane(pane_id)
    if not window_id:
        return None
    if read_window_labels(
        window_id, who, tmux_server_key,
    ) is None:
        return None
    return window_id
@

\subsubsection{Hidden Detached Commands}

The focus hooks run inside tmux's [[run-shell]], which launches a
fresh Python process.  We therefore provide hidden CLI commands that
can be called safely from hooks.  Pane tracking still uses the direct
[[_suspend-detached]]/[[_resume-detached]] pair, while window tracking
uses three event-sensor commands that append to the deferred buffer.

Window exit cleanup is a fourth hidden command.  Unlike the focus
sensors, it cannot derive the window from a live [[TMUX_PANE]] because
the pane may already be dead when the exit hook runs.  We therefore pass
the explicit [[window_id]] and remove only that pane's contributed label
names from the shared window state.

This separation matters because terminal blur alone does not prove that
the user changed tmux windows.  The focus hooks merely record candidate
[[stop]] and [[start]] events; only after [[session-window-changed]]
records whether the destination window is tracked does the shared buffer
decide whether to execute stop+start, stop-only, or start-only.

<<argument and option definitions>>=
pane_id_opt = typer.Option(
