\subsubsection{Installing Focus Hooks}

Unlike the exit hooks, which use a pane-existence check (see
[[install_tmux_exit_hooks]]), focus hooks use tmux's format-string
pane-ID comparison ([[#{==:#{pane_id},...}]]).  The distinction
matters: exit hooks fire \emph{after} a pane dies, so we must ask
whether the tracked pane still exists; focus hooks fire while the
tracked pane is alive, so [[#{pane_id}]] correctly resolves to the
pane that gained or lost focus and we can compare it directly.

<<helper functions>>=
def install_tmux_focus_hooks(
    pane_id: str,
    who: str,
    tmux_server_key: str,
) -> None:
    """Install pane-focus-out and pane-focus-in hooks.

    The hooks use a format-string pane-ID guard (not the
    pane-existence check used by exit hooks) because
    focus events fire while the tracked pane is alive.
    """
    suspend_cmd = build_detached_suspend_command(
        who, pane_id, tmux_server_key,
    )
    resume_cmd = build_detached_resume_command(
        who, pane_id, tmux_server_key,
    )
    for hook_name, shell_cmd in (
        ("pane-focus-out", suspend_cmd),
        ("pane-focus-in", resume_cmd),
    ):
        guarded = (
            "if-shell -F "
            f"'#{{==:#{{pane_id}},{pane_id}}}' "
            f"{{ run-shell -b {shlex.quote(shell_cmd)} }}"
        )
        subprocess.run(
            [
                "tmux", "set-hook", "-p",
                "-t", pane_id,
                hook_name, guarded,
            ],
            check=True,
        )
@

Window launches \emph{do} use [[pane-focus-out]] and [[pane-focus-in]],
but not to directly stop or start labels.  The problem with directly
stopping on [[pane-focus-out]] is that the event fires whenever the
terminal emulator loses focus---for example when the user Alt-Tabs to a
browser or PDF reader.  For workflows where consulting a browser is
routine, this is too aggressive: the user is still working on the task,
just not inside the terminal.

An earlier design avoided pane-focus hooks entirely for [[--window]]
mode, relying on session-scoped hooks ([[session-window-changed]],
[[client-session-changed]], etc.)\ that queried
[[window_active_clients]] at hook time.  That approach suffered from the
same terminal-blur problem: one or more of the session-scoped hooks
fired when the terminal lost focus, causing the
[[window_active_clients]] count to drop to zero and incorrectly
suspending the session.

The current design solves this with a \emph{deferred event buffer}.
All three relevant tmux events---[[pane-focus-out]],
[[pane-focus-in]], and [[session-window-changed]]---write to the same
shared file under a file lock.  Each event appends a single line:
\begin{description}
\item[[[pane-focus-out]]] appends
    [[stop <timestamp> label1 label2 ...]],
    recording both the departing labels and the time of the focus loss.
\item[[[pane-focus-in]]] appends
    [[start <timestamp> label1 label2 ...]],
    recording both the arriving labels and the time of the focus gain.
\item[[[session-window-changed]]] appends either
    [[window-switch tracked from-tracked]],
    [[window-switch tracked from-untracked]],
    [[window-switch untracked from-tracked]], or
    [[window-switch untracked from-untracked]], confirming both whether
    an actual tmux window switch occurred and whether the source and
    destination windows are tracked.
\end{description}

After every append, the hook checks a \emph{trigger condition}.  A real
switch to a tracked window may have both [[stop]] and [[start]] lines,
or only a [[start]] line when the source window was untracked.  A real
switch to an untracked window may have only a [[stop]] line.  Once the
corresponding [[window-switch ...]] marker is present, the hook executes
the deferred transition and truncates the file.

The switch marker is what filters out terminal blur.  An Alt-Tab cycle
produces candidate [[stop]]/[[start]] lines but no
[[window-switch ...]] marker, so the trigger condition is never met and
tracking continues undisturbed.  A real window switch records whether
the destination is tracked, allowing the buffer to execute the full
stop/start pair or the single-sided stop/start case that arises when
only one side of the switch is tracked.

The source annotation is what makes the start-only case safe.  Without
it, [[window-switch tracked]] plus one [[start]] line looks complete even
when tmux merely delivered [[pane-focus-in]] before the tracked source
window's [[pane-focus-out]].  By distinguishing [[from-tracked]] from
[[from-untracked]], the buffer waits for the pending [[stop]] in the
former case and still executes immediately in the latter.

Because all three hooks check the trigger condition, the mechanism is
now order-independent in the only sense that matters: whichever hook
appends the last
\emph{required} fact triggers execution.  A tracked-to-tracked switch
therefore waits for [[stop]], [[start]], and the enriched
[[window-switch ...]] marker in any order, while the one-sided tracked
or untracked cases still complete as soon as their shorter fact set is
present.

File locking ([[fcntl.flock]]) prevents races between the hooks, which
tmux may invoke as overlapping [[run-shell]] subprocesses.  The lock is
held for the duration of the append-check-execute cycle, ensuring
atomic transitions.

Those timestamped [[stop]] and [[start]] lines also preserve accurate
time accounting across hook latency.  The buffer may execute a little
later than the underlying focus event, but the deferred stop and restart
still use the recorded event times rather than [[datetime.now()]] at the
moment of execution.

Start is idempotent: calling [[start_tracking_labels]] for labels that
are already active is a no-op.  This means the brief window where both
the old and new labels may be active (if [[pane-focus-in]] fires before
[[session-window-changed]] executes the stop) is harmless.

There is one edge case where the hooks alone are insufficient, and
it is worth explaining the failure mode in detail because the seed's
shape is dictated by what goes wrong without it.

When [[run_tmux_command]] creates a new tracked window (via
[[tmux new-window]]), tmux fires [[session-window-changed]] almost
immediately.  An earlier design simply had the seed write a single
[[window-switch tracked from-untracked]] marker into the deferred
buffer and relied on the next real focus events to complete the
fact set.  The real-world failure showed up in the debug log as a
sequence like this (times from an actual 2026-04-05 incident):

\begin{quote}
\begin{tabular}{ll}
\texttt{20:36:55} & append [[window-switch tracked from-untracked]] \\
\texttt{20:36:59} & append [[stop … devel nytid]] (4 seconds later) \\
\texttt{20:52:00} & append [[start … devel nytid]] (15 minutes later) \\
\texttt{20:52:00} & \texttt{execute-switch} uses the 20:36:59 stop \\
                  & \qquad and the 20:52:00 start \\
\end{tabular}
\end{quote}

The seed's lone marker does not satisfy any of the trigger
conditions in [[<<check trigger condition>>]] (they all require at
least one [[start]] or [[stop]] line), so the marker sat waiting.
Four seconds later a real [[pane-focus-out]]---either the user
alt-tabbing to a browser or tmux emitting a spurious focus-out on a
fresh pane---deposited a [[stop]] line into the same buffer.  The
combination still did not trigger: tracked-to-tracked needs a
matching [[start]], untracked needs [[stop == start + 1]] with
[[target]] being untracked, and the marker here claims [[target]]
tracked.  Fifteen minutes later the user returned to the window, a
real [[pane-focus-in]] wrote [[start @ 20:52:00]], and the
trigger finally fired as a tracked-to-tracked switch---with
[[execute-switch]] retroactively stopping tracking at the stale
20:36:59 timestamp.  The result was a 4--6 second phantom history
entry at 20:36 and the real tracking window gone.

The old single-marker seed therefore violated the property we want for
the common [[from-untracked]] launch path: once the seed finishes, the
buffer should be either empty or already fireable, not a half-fact
waiting to be joined with whatever arrives next.  The fix enforces that
property structurally for [[from-untracked]] launches, while still
leaving [[from-tracked]] as a documented temporary exception.

We compensate in three structural ways.

\paragraph{Seed before pane focus hooks.}
[[run_tmux_command]] runs the seed \emph{before} calling
[[install_tmux_window_sync_hooks]] on the new pane.  During the
window between [[tmux new-window]] and
[[install_tmux_window_sync_hooks]] the new pane has no
[[pane-focus-out]] or [[pane-focus-in]] hook installed.  If tmux ever
delivers an initial focus event for the freshly-focused pane, it has
no subscriber and drops silently.  The seed's synthetic [[start]]
line therefore cannot later be duplicated by a stray real focus-in
event, and no stray focus-out can desync the trigger counts before
the seed has fired.  After [[install_tmux_window_sync_hooks]]
completes, every subsequent focus event is a real user action, and
those are always paired (out/in), so they cannot desync the counts
the way a single stray can.

\paragraph{Locked launch/setup phase.}
[[run_tmux_command]] holds [[with_tmux_context_lock]] across a narrow
phase that covers [[tmux new-window]], label publication, and the
[[last_selected_window]] write.  The lock begins \emph{before}
[[new-window]] so that any detached
[[session-window-changed]] hook spawned by that call must wait for the
parent to finish publishing state before it can snapshot
[[last_selected_window]].  The lock is released immediately after
[[last_selected_window]] has been updated---from that moment on, the
[[prev == selected]] guard in [[window_switch_detached]] already
discards any redundant hook event, so holding the lock longer serves
no purpose.

The lock is deliberately \emph{not} held across
[[seed_window_event_buffer]] or across
[[install_tmux_window_sync_hooks]].  For the
[[seed_window_event_buffer]] call the reason is a correctness
requirement: on the [[from-untracked]] path the seed self-triggers
[[start_tracking_labels]], which delegates to
[[mutate_worker_tracking_state]]---and that function acquires the
tmux-context lock internally by [[open]]ing the same lock file and
calling [[fcntl.flock]] on it.  Linux [[flock]] is scoped to the open
file description, not the process: a second [[open]] on the same path
from the same process produces an independent OFD whose flock call
blocks waiting for the first to release.  Holding the context lock
across the seed therefore self-deadlocks the tracked-window launch
path.  For [[install_tmux_window_sync_hooks]] the reason is simply
that [[tmux set-hook]] publishes no hook-observable state that needs
the lock; keeping it inside would widen the critical section without
benefit.

This design relies on the focus and [[session-window-changed]] hooks
being installed with [[run-shell -b]].  Without [[-b]],
[[run-shell]] is synchronous from the tmux server's point of view and
the same three-way deadlock (parent in [[subprocess.run]], tmux server
in [[run-shell]], hook process in [[flock]]) reappears.  With [[-b]],
tmux forks the hook and returns immediately, so [[new-window]]
completes, the parent finishes the locked phase and releases the lock,
and the detached hook then runs against the already-published
[[last_selected_window]] (where [[prev == selected]] discards the
now-redundant event).

\paragraph{Self-triggering seed transaction.}
For the common \emph{from-untracked} case---a new tracked window
created from an untracked source---the seed writes a complete,
immediately-fireable fact set:
\begin{enumerate}
\item [[start <now> <new_labels>]], and
\item [[window-switch tracked from-untracked]].
\end{enumerate}
By the trigger rules, this fact set matches
[[start_count == stop_count + 1]] with [[source != tracked]], so the
final append fires [[<<execute deferred window start>>]] inside
[[seed_window_event_buffer]] and truncates the buffer in the same
transaction.  The buffer is therefore empty by the time
[[install_tmux_window_sync_hooks]] installs the real focus hooks,
and no stray focus event can poison it.  The [[start_tracking_labels]]
call inside the execute path is idempotent because the synchronous
[[track start --window]] has already started the new labels, so the
synthetic fire is harmless.

For the \emph{from-tracked} case---a new tracked window created while
another tracked window was the source---the seed still writes only
the [[window-switch tracked from-tracked]] marker.  Fully
synthesizing a stop for the old labels would desync against the
real [[pane-focus-out]] that fires on the old pane (whose hooks
were already installed by its own launch), because the resulting
double-count would poison the trigger on the next real switch.  The
launch/setup lock removes the stale-context race against
[[session-window-changed]], but the deeper [[from-tracked]] half-fact
problem remains: after the seed completes, the buffer deliberately
holds that lone marker and still depends on the real stop from the old
pane.  This limitation is therefore deferred to a follow-up that will
likely need either label-aware triggering or a drain mechanism.

\paragraph{Atomic flock transaction.}
The seed uses [[seed_window_event_buffer]], which holds one
[[fcntl.flock]] across the [[ftruncate]] and the sequence of
[[_process_window_event_locked]] calls.  Concurrent tmux hook
subprocesses block on their own [[flock]] call and observe the
post-seed buffer state only once the seed releases---never an
interleaved intermediate state.  Tmux does not time out
[[run-shell]] subprocesses, so queued hooks simply wait for their
turn without event loss.

\paragraph{Redundant session hook.}
The [[prev == selected]] guard in
[[<<detached window switch command>>]] is the primary defence against
the stale-snapshot race.  If [[session-window-changed]] fires after the
parent has already written [[last_selected_window]], the hook sees the
same window ID for source and destination and discards the event.  The
narrow launch/setup lock only needs to cover the window up to that
write; once [[last_selected_window]] names the new window, the guard
handles every subsequent hook firing on its own.  The buffer
transaction independently wipes any output that landed before the seed
acquired the buffer lock.

Because multiple nytid launches may target the same tmux session, we
must avoid appending duplicate hook entries.  The
[[install_tmux_hook_once]] helper queries existing hooks first and skips
the append when the exact command string is already registered.

<<helper functions>>=
def install_tmux_hook_once(
    target: str,
    hook_name: str,
    command: str,
) -> None:
    """Append a tmux hook command once without clobbering others."""
    show_result = subprocess.run(
        ["tmux", "show-hooks", "-t", target],
        capture_output=True,
        text=True,
        check=False,
    )
    existing_lines = [
        line for line in show_result.stdout.splitlines()
        if line.startswith(f"{hook_name}[")
        or line.startswith(f"{hook_name} ")
    ]
    if any(command in line for line in existing_lines):
        return
    subprocess.run(
        [
            "tmux", "set-hook", "-a",
            "-t", target,
            hook_name,
            command,
        ],
        check=True,
    )
@

With the idempotent installer in hand, we register the three hooks that
implement the deferred event buffer.  The [[pane-focus-out]] and
[[pane-focus-in]] hooks are pane-scoped (using the same pane-ID guard as
[[install_tmux_focus_hooks]]), while [[session-window-changed]] is
session-scoped (using [[install_tmux_hook_once]] to avoid duplicates).

<<helper functions>>=
def install_tmux_window_sync_hooks(
    session_id: str,
    pane_id: str,
    who: str,
    tmux_server_key: str,
) -> None:
    """Install deferred event buffer hooks for window tracking."""
    focus_out_cmd = build_detached_window_focus_out_command(
        who, pane_id, tmux_server_key, session_id,
    )
    focus_in_cmd = build_detached_window_focus_in_command(
        who, pane_id, tmux_server_key, session_id,
    )
    for hook_name, shell_cmd in (
        ("pane-focus-out", focus_out_cmd),
        ("pane-focus-in", focus_in_cmd),
    ):
        guarded = (
            "if-shell -F "
            f"'#{{==:#{{pane_id}},{pane_id}}}' "
            f"{{ run-shell -b {shlex.quote(shell_cmd)} }}"
        )
        subprocess.run(
            [
                "tmux", "set-hook", "-p",
                "-t", pane_id,
                hook_name, guarded,
            ],
            check=True,
        )
    switch_cmd = build_detached_window_switch_command(
        who, tmux_server_key, session_id,
    )
    switch_hook = f"run-shell -b {shlex.quote(switch_cmd)}"
    install_tmux_hook_once(
        session_id,
        "session-window-changed",
        switch_hook,
    )
@

\subsubsection{Cleaning Up Suspend State on Pane Exit}

When a pane exits while unfocused, the focus-out hook has already
written a suspend state file that no focus-in will ever read.  Rather
than complicating [[_stop-detached]] with an optional [[--pane-id]]
argument (which would require the pane ID to be known before the
on-exit shell command is built), we install a lightweight cleanup
hook that removes both the suspend state file and the pane labels
file.

The hook runs as a second [[pane-exited]] handler.  Tmux 3.2+
allows multiple hooks on the same event by appending with
[[set-hook -a]].  The guard uses the same pane-existence check
as the main exit hooks (see above).

<<helper functions>>=
def install_tmux_suspend_cleanup_hook(
    pane_id: str,
    who: str,
    tmux_server_key: str,
) -> None:
    """Install a pane-exit hook that deletes suspend and pane-labels files."""
    state_file = suspend_state_path(
        pane_id, who, tmux_server_key,
    )
    labels_file = pane_labels_path(
        pane_id, who, tmux_server_key,
    )
    cleanup_cmd = (
        f"rm -f {shlex.quote(str(state_file))}"
        f" {shlex.quote(str(labels_file))}"
    )
    guarded = (
        "if-shell "
        f"'! tmux display-message -p -t {pane_id}"
        f' "" 2>/dev/null\' '
        f"{{ run-shell {shlex.quote(cleanup_cmd)} }}"
    )
    for hook_name in ("pane-exited", "pane-died"):
        subprocess.run(
            [
                "tmux", "set-hook", "-ap",
                "-t", pane_id,
                hook_name, guarded,
            ],
            check=True,
        )
@

Window cleanup must be more precise than pane cleanup because the window
labels file is shared state.  Several panes in the same tracked window
may register labels there over time, and deleting the whole file when
one pane exits would erase labels still owned by surviving work.

We therefore install a cleanup hook that removes only the labels this
launch contributed.  The deferred event buffer is \emph{not} removed
here, even though it also belongs to the same worker, because that
buffer is shared across all tracked windows for that worker.  If one
tracked pane were to delete the shared buffer while another tracked
window was still alive, it could discard pending stop/start events that
belong to the surviving window.

The guard still protects against inherited cleanup hooks in descendant
panes or windows.  Unlike the session dispatcher hooks, this cleanup
hook must be pane-scoped so it disappears together with the pane that
created the tracked shell.

<<helper functions>>=
def install_tmux_window_cleanup_hook(
    pane_id: str,
    window_id: str,
    who: str,
    tmux_server_key: str,
    labels: List[str],
) -> None:
    """Install cleanup hook for one pane's window labels."""
    cleanup_cmd = (
        build_detached_window_cleanup_command(
            labels,
            who,
            window_id,
            tmux_server_key,
        )
    )
    guarded = (
        "if-shell "
        f"'! tmux display-message -p -t {pane_id}"
        f' "" 2>/dev/null\' '
        f"{{ run-shell {shlex.quote(cleanup_cmd)} }}"
    )
    for hook_name in ("pane-exited", "pane-died"):
        subprocess.run(
            [
                "tmux", "set-hook", "-ap",
                "-t", pane_id,
                hook_name,
                guarded,
            ],
            check=True,
        )
@

The track-finalize command builder still does not need a [[pane_id]]
parameter.  Pane-specific cleanup is handled either by [[_stop-detached]]
while the pane is still alive or by the dedicated window-cleanup hook
above once the pane is gone.

<<helper functions>>=
def build_detached_track_finalize_command(
    labels: List[str], who: str,
) -> str:
    """Return shell command to stop tracking when pane exits."""
    prefix = build_detached_nytid_prefix()
    label_args = " ".join(
        shlex.quote(lbl) for lbl in labels
    )
    cmd = (
        f"{prefix} "
        f"_stop-detached {label_args}"
    )
    if who != default_username:
        cmd += f" --who {shlex.quote(who)}"
    return cmd
@

The [[_stop-detached]] hidden command must also unregister labels from any
tracked tmux context.  It delegates that cleanup to
[[stop_tracking_labels()]] with tmux context updates left enabled, so the
same start/stop helper owns both the active-session mutation and the pane or
window bookkeeping.  Since [[_stop-detached]] runs inside the tmux pane,
[[$TMUX_PANE]] is available and the delegated unregister logic can locate the
correct pane and window labels files.  Without this cleanup, labels from
finished detached commands accumulate in the pane labels file and interfere
with auto-suspend.

<<detached finalize command>>=
@cli.command(name="_stop-detached", hidden=True)
def stop_detached(
    labels: Annotated[List[str], detached_labels_arg],
    who: Annotated[str, who_opt] = default_username,
):
    """Stop labels quietly when a detached tmux pane exits."""
    session, completed_entries = stop_tracking_labels(
        who=who,
        labels=labels,
        quiet_if_missing=True,
        update_tmux_context=True,
    )
