\subsection{Blocking Command Execution}

When [[start]] launches a command, it must stop the labels afterwards no
matter how the child terminates.  That includes normal exit, an error code,
and signals such as Ctrl+C.

\paragraph{Signal handling.}
Pressing Ctrl+C in a terminal sends [[SIGINT]] to the entire
foreground \emph{process group}, which includes both nytid and the
child.  Without special handling the Python runtime raises
[[KeyboardInterrupt]] in the parent at the same moment the child
receives the signal, interrupting the tracking bookkeeping before
it has a chance to complete.

The correct POSIX approach is to ignore [[SIGINT]] in the
parent for the duration of the child's execution.
[[subprocess.run]] applies [[restore_signals=True]] by default,
which resets any [[SIG_IGN]] signals to [[SIG_DFL]] in the child
before [[exec]]---so the child still terminates on Ctrl+C as
expected, while the parent continues executing and stops the
session cleanly.  The original handler is restored in a [[finally]]
clause so it is always reinstated even if the child raises another
exception.

The tmux variants preserve the same contract.  They still block until the
tracked process ends, but the waiting happens through tmux pane hooks rather
than by waiting directly on the child process in the current terminal.

We keep the launch path split into four phases so the lifecycle is visible in
the literate source: announce what is about to happen, run the child, stop the
labels that were started for that launch, and report the result.

After stopping the launched labels we must also unregister them from any
tracked tmux context.  The pane itself survives after a [[-c]] command
exits, so without explicit cleanup the pane labels file would accumulate
stale entries that confuse auto-suspend.

Normal command exit has one subtle race with auto-suspend: by the time the
child process exits, switching away from the pane or window may already have
stopped those labels.  In that case [[stop_tracking_labels()]] quite rightly
returns no completed entries, but the tmux context still needs to forget that
the command ever owned those labels.  We therefore unregister the labels that
this launch started, rather than inferring cleanup from what happened to still
be active at process exit.

<<launch subprocess if requested>>=
if launch_requested:
    launch_start_time = datetime.datetime.now()
    <<announce launch>>
    <<run launched process>>
    if exit_code is None:
        typer.echo(
            "Tracking will stop automatically "
            "when the pane exits."
        )
        raise typer.Exit(0)
    <<stop launched labels>>
    <<unregister launched labels from tracked tmux context>>
    <<report launch result>>
    raise typer.Exit(exit_code)
@

<<announce launch>>=
if command_text is not None:
    typer.echo(
        f"Running '{command_text}' and tracking with "
        f"labels: {', '.join(sorted(launch_owned_labels))}"
    )
elif pane:
    typer.echo(
        f"Opening tracked shell in tmux pane with "
        f"labels: {', '.join(sorted(launch_owned_labels))}"
    )
else:
    typer.echo(
        f"Opening tracked shell in tmux window with "
        f"labels: {', '.join(sorted(launch_owned_labels))}"
    )
@

<<run launched process>>=
focus_labels_for_tmux = (
    tracking_labels if use_auto_suspend else None
)
focus_who_for_tmux = (
    who if use_auto_suspend else None
)
focus_window_for_tmux = (
    bool(window and use_auto_suspend)
)
try:
    if pane or window:
        if block:
            exit_code = run_tmux_command(
                command_args,
                cwd=proc_cwd,
                env=proc_env,
                window=window,
                window_name=window_name,
                focus_labels=focus_labels_for_tmux,
                focus_who=focus_who_for_tmux,
                focus_window=focus_window_for_tmux,
            )
        else:
            <<set up non-blocking tmux launch>>
    else:
        <<run direct subprocess>>
except subprocess.CalledProcessError as exc:
    typer.echo(
        f"tmux failed with exit code "
        f"{exc.returncode}",
        err=True,
    )
    exit_code = 1
except subprocess.TimeoutExpired:
    typer.echo(
        f"Command timed out after {timeout}",
        err=True,
    )
    exit_code = 124
except FileNotFoundError:
    typer.echo(
        f"Command not found: {command_args[0]}",
        err=True,
    )
    exit_code = 127
finally:
    cleanup_prompted_shell_command(
        prompt_file, prompt_dir
    )
@

For the non-blocking case, we create a temporary file for exit status
and set up a finalize command that calls [[track stop]] when the pane
exits.  The [[run_tmux_command]] function installs tmux hooks that
execute the command automatically.

<<set up non-blocking tmux launch>>=
exit_fd, exit_code_file = tempfile.mkstemp(
    prefix="nytid-track-",
    suffix=".status",
)
os.close(exit_fd)
finalize_cmd = \
    build_detached_track_finalize_command(
        launch_owned_labels, who
    )
finalize_cmd += (
    f"; rm -f {shlex.quote(exit_code_file)}"
)
run_tmux_command(
    command_args,
    cwd=proc_cwd,
    env=proc_env,
    window=window,
    window_name=window_name,
    block=False,
    exit_status_file=exit_code_file,
    on_exit_shell=finalize_cmd,
    focus_labels=focus_labels_for_tmux,
    focus_who=focus_who_for_tmux,
    focus_window=focus_window_for_tmux,
)
exit_code = None
@

For the direct subprocess branch, we ignore [[SIGINT]] in the
parent (see the signal handling discussion above) and optionally apply
a timeout.

<<run direct subprocess>>=
old_sigint = signal.signal(
    signal.SIGINT, signal.SIG_IGN
)
try:
    timeout_secs = (
        parse_timeout(timeout) if timeout
        else None
    )
    result = subprocess.run(
        command_args,
        capture_output=False,
        cwd=proc_cwd,
        timeout=timeout_secs,
    )
    exit_code = result.returncode
finally:
    signal.signal(signal.SIGINT, old_sigint)
@

<<stop launched labels>>=
launched_labels = list(launch_owned_labels)
end_time = datetime.datetime.now()
session, completed_entries = stop_tracking_labels(
    who=who,
    labels=launched_labels,
    end_time=end_time,
    quiet_if_missing=True,
)
@

The launch cleanup path must unregister every label this launch owned even
when some were only borrowed via [[--continue]] or were already auto-suspended
before the subprocess exited.  Using the freshly computed
[[completed_entries]] would miss those cases and leave stale window or pane
declarations behind.

<<unregister launched labels from tracked tmux context>>=
if launched_labels:
    unregister_tmux_context_labels(
        launched_labels, who,
    )
@

<<report launch result>>=
duration = end_time - launch_start_time
if command_text is not None:
    typer.echo(
        f"Command completed in "
        f"{format_duration(duration)}"
    )
else:
    typer.echo(
        f"Shell completed in "
        f"{format_duration(duration)}"
    )
@

\subsection{Add Command}

The [[add]] command lets users record time spent away from the computer:
meetings at the whiteboard, phone calls, travel.  The entry is complete
(it has both a start and an end time) from the moment it is created, so
it goes straight to the history file without touching the active session.

<<argument and option definitions>>=
add_labels_arg = typer.Argument(
    ..., help="Labels for the time entry",
    autocompletion=complete_historical_labels)
duration_opt = typer.Option(
    "--duration", "-d",
    help="Duration (hours unless suffixed, "
         "e.g. 1.5, 1.5h, 90m, 5400s)")
add_description_opt = typer.Option(
    "--description",
    help="Description for this time entry")
@

The original implementation had a [[--start-offset]] option that accepted
an integer (minutes only).  This was inconsistent with the string-based
[[--offset]] option on [[track start]] which accepts suffixes like
\enquote{30m} or \enquote{1.5h}.  We replace [[--start-offset]] with the
same [[--offset]] and [[--at]] pair used by [[track start]], so users need
to learn only one set of time-specification options.

<<add command>>=
@cli.command()
def add(
    labels: Annotated[List[str], add_labels_arg],
    duration: Annotated[str, duration_opt],
    offset: Annotated[Optional[str],
                      offset_opt] = None,
    at: Annotated[Optional[str], at_opt] = None,
    description: Annotated[str,
                           add_description_opt] = "",
    who: Annotated[str, who_opt] = default_username,
):
    """
    Add a completed time entry for work that already happened.

    Use this for meetings, hallway conversations, or whiteboard sessions that
    were never started in the tracker while they were happening.

    \b
    Examples:
      nytid track add meeting --duration 1
      nytid track add DD1310 supervision --duration 45m --offset -90m
      nytid track add admin --duration 30m --at 14:00 --description "Timesheet review"
    """
    if not labels:
        typer.echo(
            "Error: At least one label is required",
            err=True
        )
        raise typer.Exit(1)

    hours = parse_hours(duration)
    if hours <= 0:
        typer.echo(
            "Error: Duration must be positive",
            err=True
        )
        raise typer.Exit(1)

    <<resolve add start time>>

    end_time = start_time + datetime.timedelta(
        hours=hours
    )

    entry = TrackingEntry(
        start_time, end_time, labels, description,
        who=who
    )
    add_completed_entries([entry])

    typer.echo(
        f"Added entry: "
        f"{get_labels_display(labels)} "
        f"({format_duration(entry.duration())})"
    )
    if description:
        typer.echo(f"Description: {description}")
    typer.echo(
        f"Time: {start_time.strftime('%H:%M')} - "
        f"{end_time.strftime('%H:%M')}"
    )
@

[[--offset]] and [[--at]] are mutually exclusive for the same reason as
in [[track start]]: they address the same question (when did this session
start?) from two different angles, and combining them would be ambiguous.

<<resolve add start time>>=
if offset is not None and at is not None:
    typer.echo(
        "Error: Cannot use both --offset and --at",
        err=True
    )
    raise typer.Exit(1)

now = datetime.datetime.now()
start_time = now

if at is not None:
    try:
        start_time = parse_at_time(at)
    except ValueError as e:
        typer.echo(f"Error: {e}", err=True)
        raise typer.Exit(1)
elif offset is not None:
    try:
        start_time += parse_offset(offset)
    except ValueError as e:
        typer.echo(
            f"Error parsing offset '{offset}': {e}",
            err=True
        )
        raise typer.Exit(1)
@

\subsection{Shared Entry Filtering}

Three analysis commands ([[ls]], [[stats]], [[export]]) share the same
load-then-filter pattern.  When the filtering logic was inlined in each
command, adding a new filter dimension (such as the [[--who]] flag)
required updating every command in lock-step --- a maintenance hazard
that invited subtle inconsistencies.  Extracting the pipeline into a
single helper means that a new filter dimension is added once and all
commands benefit.  Each command still owns its error messages and
early-return logic, keeping presentation concerns separate from
filtering policy.

The stats command adds one extra step on top of this shared helper.
[[ls]] and [[export]] interpret [[--days]] as a rolling age limit, but
[[stats]] presents named calendar dates.  It therefore narrows the
already-filtered entries to the requested date range with
[[filter_entries_for_stats_window()]] so the summary and the daily table
agree even around midnight.

<<helper functions>>=
def filter_entries(
    days=None, who=None, labels=None
):
    """Load and filter tracking entries.

    Returns filtered list, or None if no data file
    exists or it is empty.
    """
    entries = load_tracking_data()
    if not entries:
        return None

    if days is not None:
        cutoff = (
            datetime.datetime.now()
            - datetime.timedelta(days=days)
        )
        entries = [
            e for e in entries
            if e.start_time >= cutoff
        ]

    if who is not None:
        entries = [
            e for e in entries
            if e.who == who
        ]

    if labels:
        entries = [
            e for e in entries
            if any(label in e.labels for label in labels)
        ]

    return entries
@

We unit-test the shared [[filter_entries]] helper directly to confirm
each filter dimension works independently:

<<test functions>>=
def test_filter_entries(temp_tracking_dir):
    """Test the shared filter_entries helper."""
    runner.invoke(cli, [
        "add", "DD1310", "grading",
        "--duration", "1",
        "--who", "alice"
    ])
    runner.invoke(cli, [
        "add", "DD1321", "lecture",
        "--duration", "45m",
        "--who", "bob"
    ])

    # No filters --- returns all
    all_entries = filter_entries()
    assert len(all_entries) == 2

    # Filter by worker
    alice = filter_entries(who="alice")
    assert len(alice) == 1
    assert alice[0].who == "alice"

    # Filter by label
    grading = filter_entries(labels=["grading"])
    assert len(grading) == 1
    assert "grading" in grading[0].labels

    # Filter by days (all recent)
    recent = filter_entries(days=1)
    assert len(recent) == 2

    # Combined filters
    result = filter_entries(
        who="alice", labels=["DD1310"]
    )
    assert len(result) == 1

def test_filter_entries_for_stats_window_uses_calendar_days():
    """Stats windows use calendar dates, not rolling 24-hour cutoffs."""
    now = datetime.datetime(2026, 3, 12, 7, 0, 0)
    entries = [
        TrackingEntry(
            datetime.datetime(2026, 3, 11, 23, 30, 0),
            datetime.datetime(2026, 3, 12, 1, 0, 0),
            ["overnight"],
        ),
        TrackingEntry(
            datetime.datetime(2026, 3, 11, 8, 0, 0),
            datetime.datetime(2026, 3, 11, 9, 0, 0),
            ["yesterday"],
        ),
        TrackingEntry(
            datetime.datetime(2026, 3, 12, 10, 0, 0),
            datetime.datetime(2026, 3, 12, 11, 0, 0),
            ["today"],
        ),
    ]

    filtered = filter_entries_for_stats_window(
        entries,
        days=1,
        now=now,
    )

    assert len(filtered) == 2
    assert filtered[0].labels == ["overnight"]
    assert filtered[0].start_time == datetime.datetime(2026, 3, 12, 0, 0, 0)
    assert filtered[0].end_time == datetime.datetime(2026, 3, 12, 1, 0, 0)
    assert filtered[1].labels == ["today"]

def test_merge_duplicate_tracking_entries_warns(caplog):
    """Exact duplicate history rows are collapsed with a warning."""
    entry = TrackingEntry(
        datetime.datetime(2026, 3, 12, 10, 0, 0),
        datetime.datetime(2026, 3, 12, 11, 0, 0),
        ["lecture"],
        "Weekly sync",
        who="dbosk",
    )

    with caplog.at_level(logging.WARNING):
        merged = merge_duplicate_tracking_entries([entry, entry])

    assert len(merged) == 1
    assert "Merged 1 duplicate tracking entry" in caplog.text

def test_normalize_tracking_entries_reports_duplicate_count(caplog):
    """Normalization reports how many duplicates were removed."""
    entry = TrackingEntry(
        datetime.datetime(2026, 3, 12, 10, 0, 0),
        datetime.datetime(2026, 3, 12, 11, 0, 0),
        ["lecture"],
        who="dbosk",
    )

    with caplog.at_level(logging.WARNING):
        merged, duplicate_count = normalize_tracking_entries([entry, entry])

    assert len(merged) == 1
    assert duplicate_count == 1
    assert "Merged 1 duplicate tracking entry" in caplog.text
