\subsection{Stats Command}

The stats command answers a question teachers ask constantly:
\enquote{How much time did I actually spend on this?}  The default view
answers the most immediate version of that question:
\enquote{what did today look like?}  A one-day default makes [[stats]] a
quick daily review, while [[-n]]/[[--days]] expands the window when the
user wants a longer retrospective.

The default output is aggregated, but not flattened into individual
labels.  Teachers often work in repeated bursts on the same combination
of tags, such as [[nytid]], [[devel]], and [[work]].  Listing each
session separately is noisy, but listing each label individually falsely
suggests a hierarchy.  Grouping by the exact label set keeps the tags
equal while still collapsing repeated work into one line per day.

Warnings remain part of the optional summary view.  Their threshold is
prorated: if the window is 3 days and the weekly limit is 40 hours, we
warn after 40 * 3/7 ≈ 17 hours rather than a fixed 40. This keeps the
warning meaningful for both short and long windows.

The window length and summary toggle are the two defaults worth
configuring per user; the weekly/daily limits are already config-backed
elsewhere.
<<constants>>=
TRACK_STATS_DAYS_CONFIG = "track.stats.days"
TRACK_STATS_SUMMARY_CONFIG = "track.stats.summary"

DEFAULT_TRACK_STATS_DAYS = default(TRACK_STATS_DAYS_CONFIG, 1, int)
DEFAULT_TRACK_STATS_SUMMARY = default(TRACK_STATS_SUMMARY_CONFIG,
                                      False, bool)
@

<<argument and option definitions>>=
stats_labels_arg = typer.Argument(
    help="Filter statistics by specific labels "
         "(shows all if not specified)",
    autocompletion=complete_historical_labels)
stats_days_opt = typer.Option(
    "--days", "-n",
    help="Number of days to include in stats. "
         "[config: track.stats.days]")
weekly_limit_opt = typer.Option(
    "--weekly-limit",
    help="Weekly hour limit for warnings "
         "(uses config default if not specified). "
         "[config: track.weekly_limit]")
daily_limit_opt = typer.Option(
    "--daily-limit",
    help="Daily hour limit for warnings "
         "(uses config default if not specified). "
         "[config: track.daily_limit]")
summary_opt = typer.Option(
    "--summary",
    help="Include an overall summary "
         "for the whole window. "
         "[config: track.stats.summary]")
@

<<stats command>>=
@cli.command()
def stats(
    labels: Annotated[List[str],
                      stats_labels_arg] = None,
    days: Annotated[int,
                    stats_days_opt] = DEFAULT_TRACK_STATS_DAYS,
    weekly_limit: Annotated[Optional[float],
                            weekly_limit_opt] = None,
    daily_limit: Annotated[Optional[float],
                           daily_limit_opt] = None,
    who: Annotated[Optional[str],
                   who_filter_opt] = None,
    summary: Annotated[bool,
                       summary_opt] = DEFAULT_TRACK_STATS_SUMMARY,
):
    """
    Show aggregated statistics for recent tracking history.

    Use this to see how much time went to a course, compare the last few days,
    or check whether the workload exceeds configured daily or weekly limits.

    \b
    Examples:
      nytid track stats
      nytid track stats DD1310 lecture
      nytid track stats -n 7 --summary
      nytid track stats --who Dan-Claude
    """
    <<resolve stats limits>>
    <<load and filter entries for stats>>
    <<display stats summary when requested>>
    <<display grouped daily breakdown>>
@

The [[--weekly-limit]] and [[--daily-limit]] flags are optional because
users should be able to configure sensible defaults once and forget about
them. When neither flag nor configuration is present the module falls
back to the built-in constants:

<<resolve stats limits>>=
if weekly_limit is None:
    weekly_limit = get_default_weekly_limit()
if daily_limit is None:
    daily_limit = get_default_daily_limit()
@

With the shared helper handling the mechanical filtering, this chunk
focuses on the stats-specific concerns: constructing [[label_filter_msg]]
for headers, generating the full requested date range, and
distinguishing \enquote{no data at all} ([[None]]) from
\enquote{data exists but nothing matched the filter}.  We no longer
return early on an empty result, because an empty day still belongs in a
daily report as [[0s]].

The extra wrinkle is that the stats report names calendar dates, so its
window must also be calendar-based.  Using [[filter_entries(days=1)]]
would mean 
\enquote{the last 24 hours,} which can exclude early-morning work from
today while including late-evening work from yesterday.  We therefore
load by worker and labels first, then apply
[[filter_entries_for_stats_window()]] with a single captured
[[stats_now]] timestamp so the filter and the rendered date headers agree:

<<load and filter entries for stats>>=
stats_now = datetime.datetime.now()
recent_entries = filter_entries(
    who=who, labels=labels
)

if recent_entries is None:
    typer.echo("No tracking data available")
    return

recent_entries = filter_entries_for_stats_window(
    recent_entries,
    days=days,
    now=stats_now,
)

if labels:
    label_filter_msg = (
        f" for labels: {', '.join(labels)}"
    )
else:
    label_filter_msg = ""

stats_dates = make_stats_dates(days, now=stats_now)
daily_totals = compute_daily_wall_clock(recent_entries)
daily_label_set_totals = compute_daily_label_set_totals(
    recent_entries
)
@

The optional summary keeps the old big-picture view for users who want a
single total for the whole window before the daily details:

<<display stats summary when requested>>=
total_time = merge_intervals(recent_entries)
total_hours = total_time.total_seconds() / 3600

if summary:
    typer.echo(
        f"Statistics for the last {days} days"
        f"{label_filter_msg}:"
    )
    typer.echo(
        f"Total time: {format_duration(total_time)}"
        f" ({total_hours:.1f} hours)"
    )
    typer.echo(
        f"Average per day: {total_hours/days:.1f} hours"
    )

    if total_hours > (weekly_limit * days / 7):
        typer.echo(
            f"⚠️  Warning: Exceeding weekly limit of"
            f" {weekly_limit} hours per week",
            err=True,
        )
    typer.echo()
@

The default report iterates across the full requested date range, newest
first, so days without activity still appear.  Within each day we sort
label sets by duration descending and render the tags with commas to
emphasise that they are peers rather than a hierarchy.

Presentation matters here because stats is read comparatively: users
scan down a column to compare durations and across a row to connect a
day with its label sets.  We therefore render the data as a table.  In a
terminal we use [[rich]] for aligned columns; when stdout is not a tty we
fall back to a plain-text table so redirected output and tests stay
readable.

We keep row construction separate from rendering.  That gives both the
rich and plain-text paths the same content, and it makes the dependency
explicit: renderers consume precomputed [[rows]] rather than rebuilding
the report format themselves.

<<display grouped daily breakdown>>=
<<build stats table rows>>
<<render stats table>>
@

<<build stats table rows>>=
rows = []
for date in stats_dates:
    label_totals = daily_label_set_totals.get(date, {})
    duration = daily_totals.get(date, datetime.timedelta())
    hours = duration.total_seconds() / 3600
    total_text = format_duration(duration)
    if hours > daily_limit:
        total_text += " !"

    if not label_totals:
        rows.append((str(date), total_text, "(off)", "0s"))
        continue

    first_row = True

    for labels_key, labels_duration in sorted(
        label_totals.items(),
        key=lambda item: (-item[1].total_seconds(), item[0]),
    ):
        rows.append(
            (
                str(date) if first_row else "",
                total_text if first_row else "",
                ", ".join(labels_key),
                format_duration(labels_duration),
            )
        )
        first_row = False
@

The renderer now has a single job: choose the presentation layer.  The
TTY path gets [[rich]] with column-aware wrapping, while the fallback
path stays pure ASCII and aligned for pipes, logs, and tests:

<<render stats table>>=
if sys.stdout.isatty():
    <<render stats table with rich>>
else:
    <<render stats table as plain columns>>
@

The two rendering paths share the same rows so they differ only in
presentation, not in content.  Rich gets automatic column sizing and box
drawing, while the plain-text path computes widths and prints an aligned
ASCII table:

<<render stats table with rich>>=
from rich.console import Console
from rich import box
from rich.table import Table

console = Console()
table = Table(
    show_header=True,
    header_style="bold",
    box=box.SIMPLE,
    show_edge=False,
    pad_edge=False,
)
table.add_column("Date", style="cyan", no_wrap=True)
table.add_column("Total", justify="right", no_wrap=True)
table.add_column("Labels", overflow="fold")
table.add_column("Time", justify="right", no_wrap=True)

for row in rows:
    table.add_row(*row)

console.print(table)
@

<<render stats table as plain columns>>=
headers = ("Date", "Total", "Labels", "Time")
date_width = max(len(headers[0]), *(len(row[0]) for row in rows))
total_width = max(len(headers[1]), *(len(row[1]) for row in rows))
labels_width = max(len(headers[2]), *(len(row[2]) for row in rows))
time_width = max(len(headers[3]), *(len(row[3]) for row in rows))

typer.echo(
    f"{headers[0]:<{date_width}}  "
    f"{headers[1]:<{total_width}}  "
    f"{headers[2]:<{labels_width}}  "
    f"{headers[3]:>{time_width}}"
)
typer.echo(
    f"{'-' * date_width}  "
    f"{'-' * total_width}  "
    f"{'-' * labels_width}  "
    f"{'-' * time_width}"
)
for date, total, labels_text, labels_time in rows:
    typer.echo(
        f"{date:<{date_width}}  "
        f"{total:<{total_width}}  "
        f"{labels_text:<{labels_width}}  "
        f"{labels_time:>{time_width}}".rstrip()
    )
@

\subsection{Export Command}

Unlike stats, which summarises data for on-screen reading, export
produces machine-readable output for import into external tools.
Three formats cover the main use cases: \textsc{ics} for calendar
applications (time entries appear as calendar events so you can see
where your time went visually), JSON for programmatic consumption, and
CSV for spreadsheet analysis.  We use [[VEVENT]] (not [[VTODO]]) for
\textsc{ics} because tracking entries are \emph{completed} work
sessions with known start and end times --- exactly what a calendar
event represents.

The CSV header is conditionally included: when writing to a file or
printing to a terminal we include it for human readability; when piping
to another command we omit it so tools like [[awk]] and [[cut]] see
only data rows.

We use an [[Enum]] for the format parameter so that Typer automatically
provides shell completion for the three valid choices, mirroring the
approach used by [[OutputFormat]] in the schedule module:

<<constants>>=
class ExportFormat(str, Enum):
    ics = "ics"
    json = "json"
    csv = "csv"
@

<<argument and option definitions>>=
export_format_opt = typer.Option(
    "--format", "-f",
    help="Export format (ics, json, csv)")
export_days_opt = typer.Option(
    "--days",
    help="Number of days to export")
export_output_opt = typer.Option(
    "--output", "-o",
    help="Output file (stdout if not specified)")
@

<<export command>>=
@cli.command()
def export(
    format: Annotated[ExportFormat,
                      export_format_opt] = ExportFormat.ics,
    days: Annotated[int, export_days_opt] = 30,
    output: Annotated[Optional[str],
                      export_output_opt] = None,
    who: Annotated[Optional[str],
                   who_filter_opt] = None,
):
    """
    Export tracking history as ICS, JSON, or CSV.

    Use ICS for calendar import, JSON for scripting, and CSV for spreadsheets
    or reporting tools.

    \b
    Examples:
      nytid track export --format json
      nytid track export --format csv --output tracking.csv
      nytid track export --format ics --days 7
    """
    filtered_entries = filter_entries(
        days=days, who=who
    )

    if filtered_entries is None:
        typer.echo("No tracking data to export", err=True)
        return

    if not filtered_entries:
        typer.echo(
            f"No tracking data in the last {days} days",
            err=True,
        )
        return

    if format == ExportFormat.ics:
        export_data = export_to_ics(filtered_entries)
    elif format == ExportFormat.json:
        export_data = export_to_json(filtered_entries)
    elif format == ExportFormat.csv:
        export_data = export_to_csv(
            filtered_entries,
            include_header=(
                sys.stdout.isatty() or bool(output)
            ),
        )

    if output:
        with open(output, 'w') as f:
            f.write(export_data)
        typer.echo(
            f"Exported {len(filtered_entries)}"
            f" entries to {output}"
        )
    else:
        print(export_data)
@

\subsubsection{ICS Export}

Time entries map directly to [[VEVENT]] components.  We use the
entry's labels as iCalendar categories so that calendar apps can
filter events by course or activity type.  The [[ics]] package is an
optional dependency; a clear error is raised when it is absent so the
user knows exactly what to install.

Tracking entries store naive local datetimes (from
[[datetime.datetime.now()]]).
The [[ics]] library interprets naive datetimes as UTC, so we must
wrap them with the local timezone via [[arrowlib.get]] to prevent
calendar apps from displaying shifted times.
<<ics export function>>=
def export_to_ics(entries: List[TrackingEntry]) -> str:
    """Export entries as VEVENT components in ICS format.

    Labels are exposed as iCalendar categories so that
    calendar apps can filter by course or activity.
    """
    try:
        import ics.icalendar
        import ics.event
        import arrow as arrowlib
        import dateutil.tz
    except ImportError:
        typer.echo(
            "ICS export requires the 'ics' package",
            err=True,
        )
        raise typer.Exit(1)

    local_tz = dateutil.tz.tzlocal()
    calendar = ics.icalendar.Calendar()

    for entry in entries:
        event = ics.event.Event()
        event.name = (
            f"Work: {get_labels_display(entry.labels)}"
        )
        event.begin = arrowlib.get(
            entry.start_time, local_tz
        )
        event.end = arrowlib.get(
            entry.end_time, local_tz
        )

        if entry.description:
            event.description = entry.description

        if entry.labels:
            event.categories = set(entry.labels)

        calendar.events.add(event)

    return str(calendar)
@

\subsubsection{JSON Export}

JSON export is a trivial serialization of the in-memory representation.
It is included for completeness and for programmatic consumption by
scripts that need the full entry data:

<<json export function>>=
def export_to_json(entries: List[TrackingEntry]) -> str:
    """Export entries as a JSON array."""
    return json.dumps(
        [entry.to_dict() for entry in entries], indent=2
    )
@

\subsubsection{CSV Export}

CSV is the most portable format for analysis in spreadsheets and
shell pipelines.  Labels, which are a list, are joined with
[[LABEL_SEPARATOR]] into a single cell.  The header row is controlled
by the caller so that the command layer can apply TTY detection:

<<csv export function>>=
def export_to_csv(
    entries: List[TrackingEntry],
    include_header: bool = True,
) -> str:
    """Export entries to CSV format.

    When ``include_header`` is ``False`` the column-name
    row is omitted, making the output suitable for piping
    to tools like ``awk`` and ``cut``.
    """
    import io
    import csv

    output = io.StringIO()
    writer = csv.writer(output)

    if include_header:
        writer.writerow([
            'Start Time', 'End Time',
            'Duration (minutes)', 'Labels',
            'Description', 'Who'
        ])

    for entry in entries:
        duration_minutes = (
            entry.duration().total_seconds() / 60
        )
        labels_str = LABEL_SEPARATOR.join(entry.labels)
        writer.writerow([
            entry.start_time.isoformat(),
            entry.end_time.isoformat(),
            f"{duration_minutes:.1f}",
            labels_str,
            entry.description,
            entry.who
        ])

    return output.getvalue()
